The purpose of the following is to recontruct the above picture 
in the context of the linear quark-meson model. We shall take into account
the effect of fluctuations of the fields, so that the potential will have
a more complicated form than the simple assumption of eq. ().
Moreover, the nature of the
fixed points will differ from the predictions of mean field theory. 


The model 

We consider an effective action of the form

 
with . The field  includes
the  field and the three pion fields. It is parametrized as
 
where   denote the Pauli matrices. 
The fermionic field  
includes two flavours  corresponding to the
up and down quarks. The non-zero temperature effects are taken into
account by restricting the 
time integration within the finite interval
 in Euclidean space. The scalar (fermionic) fields obey 
periodic (anti-periodic) boundary conditions. We are also considering
a non-zero chemical potential, associated to the quark number density 
 that is proportional to the baryon number.


In the effective action we have omitted the wavefunction renormalization 
for both the scalar and fermionic fields. We have also neglected the
scale dependence of the Yukawa coupling . We take into account only
the scale dependence of the potential , which we assume to be a
general function of . 
Our approximation is consistent in two cases:

a) If the Yukawa coupling is small at an initial large momentum scale
, its subsequent evolution for  is expected to be slow.
The reason is that the leading contribution to  is 
. The same holds true for the wavefunction renormalizations
. The scalar field wavefunction renormalization
receives an additional contribution through scalar field contributions.
Typically this is small in three and four dimensions, 
as is obvious from the smallness of
the anomalous dimension in the pure scalar theory.

2) If partial infrared fixed points exist in the evolution equations, all
the above quantities take almost constant values. The wavefunction 
renormalizations can be set equal to 1 through the rescaling 
of the fields, while the Yukawa coupling becomes scale independent. This
scenario is realized in the low energy regime of the quark-meson model in
four dimensions, for realistic values of the quark and meson masses. 

The last term in eq. () accounts for the explicit breaking
of the chiral symmetry through the current quark masses. 
One expects .
We assume equal
masses  for the two light quarks so that
. 
The determination of
the proportionality constant requires the embedding of the 
theory described by the action () in a more fundamental
framework. For example, in refs. 
 
it was calculated
in terms of the energy scale  at which  can be
introduced as a composite field in a theory of quarks
(such as the Nambu-Jona-Lasinio model).
One obtains , with 
 the fermion wavefunction renormalization, and 
 the positive mass term in the potential of  at the
scale . This mass term becomes negative at lower energy scales
because of fermionic quantum fluctuations, and the chiral symmetry is 
spontaneously broken. In this work we set  for all  and
also neglect the running of . For this reason it is not possible to 
express  in terms of fundamental quantities. However,  can be 
fixed through the low energy dynamics. The pion
mass at the vacuum in
the presence of explicit chiral symmetry breaking is proportional
to the source term and can be used as input for its determination.



The evolution equation 

The dependence 
of the effective action
 on an infrared cutoff scale  
is given by an exact flow equation , which
for fermionic fields  (quarks) and bosonic fields  (mesons)
reads
 
Here  is the matrix of second functional derivatives of
 with respect to both fermionic and bosonic field components. The
first trace in the r.h.s. of () runs only
over the bosonic degrees of freedom. It implies a momentum integration and
a summation over flavor indices. The second trace runs over the
fermionic degrees of freedom and contains in addition a summation over
Dirac and color indices. The terms ,  are infrared cutoffs
that have been introduced in order to eliminate contributions from 
fluctuations with momenta  in the momentum integrations.



