The fermionic contribution  has a simple interpretation within
our approximate treatment. 
It consists of three parts: The term  originates in the 
quantum fluctuations of the fermionic fields, for which a mass-like infrared
cutoff  has been introduced. This type of cutoff does
not provide automatic ultraviolet regularization. This is achieved 
through the modification of the cutoff by an additional -function
. The number of degrees of freedom is 
2(flavour)2(spin)2(particle-antiparticle)
(colour).
The term  is the free energy of a non-interacting
fermionic gas of temperature  and chemical potential 
in the presence of the mass-like cutoff . The ultraviolet 
regularization has been omitted as we assume .
The number of degrees of freedom is 2(flavour)2(spin)
(colour).
The term  is the free energy of the anti-particles 
that have opposite chemical potential.
We emphasize that the evolution of  is derived starting from the
exact flow equation for the effective action of the system. 
The truncation of eq. () and the additional assumptions
of constant wavefunction renormalizations and Yukawa coupling lead to
the intuitive form of eqs. ()-().
We also point out that the use of different cutoffs for the
scalar and fermionic fields does not affect physical
quantities, as the cutoffs are removed in the limit . 


