The behaviour of  is displayed in fig. .
We observe the two minima, and the curvature of the
potential around them that determines the mass terms,
settling down at constant values. The minimum at the origin is slightly 
deeper than the one at non-zero , indicating that the temperature is
slightly larger than the critical one.  
The barrier separating the two minima remains scale dependent 
even after the minima have become scale independent to a good approximation.
This is a general feature of the solutions near first-order phase
transitions, which is related to the issue of the convexity of the
effective potential. 
As the scale-dependent
potential  approaches the effective potential for , the
barrier should disappear, giving its place to the standard Maxwell
construction. This is a general property of the solutions of the evolution
equation, which can be 
established analytically. However, the numerical integration of the 
evolution equation in this regime is difficult because of the
presence of a pole in the threshold function. For this reason, 
in fig.  we have stopped the evolution at a non-zero value of , 
such that the minima are stabilized, even though the barrier has not
disappeared yet. An example of 
a more elaborate numerical integration that displays the
approach to convexity for  is presented in ref.. 
The calculation of bubble-nucleation rates during a first-order phase
transition is performed at non-zero values of . The physical value of
the nucleation rate is independent of the choice of  at which the 
calculation is carried out.





 
