For example, the critical exponent  stays equal to 0.25 arbitrarily
close to the critical temperature.


The phase diagram for  

The analytical crossover and the first-order phase transitions 

The effect of a source term  on a second-order phase transition
has been studied extensively in the statistical physics and field theory
literature. It is well known that the phase transition disappears and
is replaced by an analytical crossover. No singularities appear in the
physical quantities. Instead these are described by smooth  functions
connecting the two "phases". 
The reason can be understood by
considering the potential for a constant value of , corresponding 
to the part of the phase diagram where a second-order
phase transition is expected for .
The vacuum of the theory is determined by
the relation . For  the vacuum is 
located away from the origin for all values of .
If we take  as the order parameter, no signal of a phase
transition exists. Moreover, both the -field and the pions are
massive at the vacuum. This implies that no significant fluctuations
exist in the deep infrared, 
as all fields decouple at sufficiently low energy scales. 
Consequently, no singularities are expected in physical quantities. 

For very small , the influence of the fixed point leads to a universal form
of the potential in the critical region. 
It is convenient to define 
the quantity , with  and  a critical
exponent. The potential can be expressed as 
1 ^  U_0  =f(x),
 with  another critical exponent and
.
The form of the function , characterized as the universal
equation of state, is completely specified by the 
universality class. For small , 
the temperature dependence of the -field and
pion masses 
near the critical temperature can be extracted from eq. () 
.

We shall not determine the equation of state of the  universality class
here, as it has been calculated in ref..
There, it is also demonstrated how the interplay between universal and
non-universal behaviour can be described efficiently by the 
effective average action. Even though the study of ref.is carried out for , it displays all the characteristic features
associated with theories in the small- region of the phase diagram. 

The 
first-order phase transitions for large  that we discussed
in subsection 7.2 are not affected significantly by the presence of
a source term . The minimum at the origin moves to a non-zero value
of , as in the case of second-order phase transitions. 
The linear term also affects the relative depth of the two
minima of the potential and chages
the value of the critical temperature.
The most characteristic feature of the phase diagram for  is the 
presence of a critical endpoint that marks the end of the line of first-order
phase transitions. At this point a second-order phase transition is expected
to take place. In the following subsection we discuss in detail the
nature of the endpoint and determine the relevant universality class.



